T1  - Review of Pain and depression. An interdisciplinary client-centered approach. Advances in psychosomatic medicine, Vol. 25.
A1  - Pridmore, Saxby

A2  - Simon, G., VonKorff, M., Piccinelli, M., Simon
Y1  - 2005//
N2  - Reviews the 25th volume of the book Pain and depression. An interdisciplinary client-centered approach. Advances in psychosomatic medicine, edited by M. R. Clark, G. J. Treisman (2004). It is well known that chronic pain is associated with high rates of psychopathology, particularly depression. There are few examples of new, ground-breaking work in the nine chapters which comprise this book. There is a chapter which conceptualizes mental disorders into spectrums of 'internalizing' disorders and 'externalizing' disorders. Some evidence indicates medically unexplained pain may be classified as an internalizing disorder. Similarities are noted with affective spectrum disorders and the general neurotic syndrome. The second half of the book is disappointing. The chapter on neurobiology of pain is especially disappointing. There are chapters which have little to do with depression, such as, 'Can we prevent a second Gulf War Syndrome?' and 'Opioid prescribing for chronic nonmalignant pain in primary care', along with considerations of the treatment of chronic pain in people with substance use disorders. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
