T1  - New gateways to dialogue in general practice: Development of an illness diary to expand communication.
A1  - Stensland, Per
A1  - Malterud, Kirsti

Y1  - 1997//
N2  - Presents the illness diary method (IDM) as the end-point of systematic elaboration, and shows how the implementation of the IDM has modified its characteristics. The IDM aims to clarify the process of problem definition in the doctor-patient consultation in general practice, create a joint language, and recognize the clinical problem in its context. Ss were 16 11-55 yr old patients with long-standing illness without clinical findings. In the IDM approach, the patient first presents his or her symptoms and the doctor may suggest the use of an illness diary. Together they shape the format of the diary and identify items to be included. The patient uses the diary for home notes between consultations. The notes constitute the frame for fresh dialogue about the complaints in the next consultation. The IDM has gradually been elaborated according to utilization experiences on an interactional level, leading to a more specific presentation of the method and how it can be used. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2022 APA, all rights reserved)
