T1  - Narrative and nonverbal communication of somatizing and nonsomatizing patients in a primary care setting.
T3  - Dissertation Abstracts International
A1  - Elderkin-Thompson, Virginia Diane

Y1  - 1997//
N2  - Approximately 20% to 30% of the primary care patient population consists of somatizing patients who tend to have multiple, recurrent symptoms without organic explanations after appropriate medical investigation. These patients make frequent medical visits and undergo numerous procedures for their illnesses, yet they have poorer outcomes than nonsomatizing patients with similar symptoms. Somatizers' symptoms are suspected of arising from unresolved social or emotional conflicts. It was hypothesized that somatizers would reflect this suppression of underlying emotional conflict during their symptom presentations by inhibiting affect in their nonverbal communication. The emotional suppression needed to constrain the conflict was also expected to be reflected qualitatively in the development of their illness narratives. First-time patients at a primary care clinic were interviewed with a structured diagnostic instrument to assess somatization, depression, anxiety and Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder (N=115). Their medical encounters were then videorecorded. Nonverbal behavior was assessed using (1) frequency and duration measures of discrete physical movements, and (2) appraisals of general appearance. Coders were blind to somatization condition. Illness narratives were examined qualitatively for structure, meaning suggested by the structure, and use of narrative development for articulating the onset of physical symptoms. Results of the analysis of nonverbal patient behavior indicated that somatizing patients were more emotionally distant and detached, and were less pleasant, affectively expressive, assertive and relaxed in medical encounters than nonsomatizers. Results of a logistic regression showed that detachment doubled the likelihood of somatization, but the presence of relaxation decreased the likelihood by 75%. Among somatizing patients, Latinos were seen as less expressive and sadder than non-Latinos. Verbal behavior of somatizers varied from that of nonsomatizers. Somatizers used well-structured narratives but they amplified the seriousness of their symptoms. Somatizers with a history of major depression used less well-developed narrative structure, focused on their histories of chronic illnesses, and attempted to control the discussion with digressions, equivocations, or ignoring of physician requests. Their narratives frequently held multiple interpretations. Somatizers diagnosed with PTSD during their lifetimes focused on concrete physical sensations and were unable to provide either contextual or chronological development in their narratives. These data indicate that many somatizing patients may be tentatively identified during initial encounters by verbal and nonverbal behaviors. Accompanying the improvement in treatment would be a reduction in the over-utilization of health care services that occurs when the underlying somatization remains unrecognized. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
